<div class="mw-heading mw-heading2">
<h2 id="Further_reading">Further reading</h2>
<span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Louis_Hartz&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Further reading"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span>
</div>
<ul>
<li>Abbott, Philip. "Still Louis Hartz after All These Years: A Defense of the Liberal Society Thesis," <i>Perspectives on Politics,</i> Vol. 3, No. 1 (Mar., 2005), pp. 93–109 <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/3688113">in JSTOR</a>
</li>
<li>Ericson, David and Louisa Green, eds. <i>The Liberal Tradition in American Politics: Reassessing the Legacy of American Liberalism</i>. 1999. Routledge.</li>
<li>Hulliung, Mark, ed. <i>The American Liberal Tradition Reconsidered: The Contested Legacy of Louis Hartz</i> (University Press of Kansas; 2010) 285 pages; essays by  scholars that reevaluate Hartz's argument that the United States is inherently liberal.</li>
<li>Kloppenberg, James T. "In Retrospect: Louis Hartz's "The Liberal Tradition in America," <i>Reviews in American History,</i> Vol. 29, No. 3 (Sept. 2001), pp. 460–478 <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/30030991">in JSTOR</a>
</li>
<li>
<a href="/wiki/Rogers_Smith" title="Rogers Smith">Smith, Rogers</a>. “Beyond Tocqueville, Myrdal and Hartz: The Multiple Traditions in America.” <i><a href="/wiki/American_Political_Science_Review" title="American Political Science Review">American Political Science Review</a></i>  1993.  87(3): 549-566.</li>
</ul>
